{"input": "[General · no RVIs] Why should we reject RVIs?", "output": "a) illogical – you shouldn’t win for being fair – it’s a litmus test for engaging in substance, b) norming – I can’t concede the counterinterp if I realize I’m wrong which forces me to argue for bad norms, c) chilling effect – forces you to split your 2AR so you can’t collapse and misconstrue the 2NR, d) topic ed – prevents 1AR blipstorm scripts and allows us to get back to substance after resolving theory.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · fairness · 2NR] Why are fairness and jurisdiction voters?", "output": "Fairness is a voter since it’s constitutive of debate and comes before education since if I can’t engage w/ the aff there’s no way to get any education. Jurisdiction is a voter since judges can’t vote on the aff if it wasn’t topical.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · no RVIs] Why should we reject RVIs?", "output": "1] Encourages theory baiting and chills checking real abuse. 2] Illogical b/c don’t win for being fair and logic is meta-constraint on arguments b/c comes lexically prior. 3] Double Bind – Either my theory shell is a] unwarranted and should be easy to respond to or b] stands because there is actual abuse in the round.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[Neg · education as a voter · 2NR] Why is education a voter?", "output": "Education is a voter because it’s the only reason schools fund debate and it's the only portable impact.", "category": "Theory", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · Yes Act-Omission Distinction] Why should we reject the act-omission distinction?", "output": "1] Infinite obligations – no act-omission means you’re culpable for every omission which is untenable: you could be curing cancer right now. \n\n2] Trolley Problem – Omissions allow us to escape culpability in otherwise unavoidable situations like when someone pulls the lever to kill 1 instead of 2 – otherwise we’re always wrong which makes morality inaccessible – outweighs on bindingness – if an agent is permanently violating ethics, they can’t take moral action.", "category": "Philosophy", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · determinism] Why does determinism deny the existence of obligations?", "output": "Determinism denies the existence of obligations because you can’t hold agents culpable for actions external to their free will since they would occur regardless of whether it was good or bad.", "category": "Philosophy", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · determinism] Why is the physical world causally deterministic?", "output": "Causal Link Chains – if all consequences are triggered by prior actions, then all actions are triggered by prior consequences, which proves a causal chain of events structure action rather than free will.\n\nBrain Activity – their bindingness warrants are all reasons why, biologically speaking, our brains are hard wired to pursue pleasure and reject pain. Our bodies take actions based off brain activity, which we have zero control over, which disproves free will.", "category": "Philosophy", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · induction fails] Why should we reject the use of induction to justify actions?", "output": "Induction fails – we can’t use the past to justify actions since it assumes those exact past events will happen the same way. Saying predictions are accurate is circular since that uses inductive reasoning to justify induction.", "category": "Philosophy", "mode": "normal"}
{"input": "[General · consequences] Why do consequences fail as a basis for ethics?", "output": "There’s no cutoff for when a consequence ends which leads to endless causal chains with infinite consequences. We only know a consequence will occur after it happens which means it can’t guide prior action. We can simply stop pursuing our desires of certain consequences and look to different ones, means it’s escapable and circular. Circumstances are always shifting and we don’t know what affects or doesn’t affect our ability to collect sufficient information to predict consequences, so our calculations require infinitely more calculation, which halts action.", "category": "Philosophy", "mode": "normal"}
